attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, not stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Felix Bilstein - yara-signator at cocacoding dot com

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a DDoS botnet agent, specifically a variant of the Gafgyt (Bashlite) or Mirai family. It performs process masquerading by renaming its process to '/usr/sbin/dropbear' via prctl and argv manipulation to evade detection. Key malicious behaviors include: 1) Command and Control (C2) communication with 185.196.41.95; 2) A telnet brute-force scanner ('StartTheLelz') that targets random public IPs with hardcoded credentials; 3) Multiple DDoS attack vectors (TCP, UDP, JUNK, and HTTP floods); and 4) Remote shell capabilities via fdpopen. A relevant IOC is the download cradle 'http://185.196.41.95/bins.sh'.
